      <li><a href="https://example.com" class="offsite-link">Example Offsite Link</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This list includes some internal controlled vocabulary that you can insert:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p><%= t('arclight.views.show.online_content.link_text') %></p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Here's a list, with each list containing sentences:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>This list item has a few sentences. There are no link inside this paragraph. This can be wrapped with just the list item tag.</li>
      <li><p>However, this list item wants you to read more <%= link_to 'about OAC', about_path %>. In order for the link to conform to our style guide (with links in paragraphs being underlined), we need to wrap this list item in p tags, in addition to the list item tag.</p></li>
    </ul>
<h2>h2: Definition List Example</h2>
    <p>This page is also a nice place to demonstrate a definition list style. Definition lists are used on the finding aid pages are are comprised of a term (dt) and a description (dd). Links in the description (dd) are underlined like links in paragraphs.</p>
    <dl>
    <dt>Term 1</dt>
    <dd>Description for term 1. This is a link in a description: <a href="https://example.com">Example Link</a>.</dd>
    <dt><a href="#">Creator</a></dt>
    <dd>Links in the dt (definition list term) don't get an underline, like the linked Creator in this example.</dd>
    </dl>
    <h2>h2: Headings List</h2>
    <h3>h3: Example Heading</h3>
    <h4>h4: Example Heading</h4>
    <h5>h5: Example Heading</h5>
    <h6>h6: Example Heading</h6>
    <p>Headings are used to organize content on the page. The h1 is the main title, and subsequent headings (h2, h3, etc.) are used for subheadings.</p>
